// Expected lowering of struct_pass/input.c.
//
// Notes:
//   - `struct Point` produces no Sutra-side declaration. The struct
//     type becomes an Axon (the carrier); the field set is implicit
//     in which keys the program reads/writes. Optionally the
//     transpiler may emit `class Point extends vector { }` as
//     documentation, but it's not needed for the lowering.
//   - Each field access `p.x` becomes `p.item("x")`.
//   - The aggregate initializer `{ .x = 3, .y = 4 }` becomes
//     `Axon p; p.add("x", 3); p.add("y", 4);` — the augmented-
//     assignment surface, which reduces to two functional updates
//     to the underlying axon vector.
//   - Within-function SSA-elision applies: in this example
//     distance_squared reads both "x" and "y", and main passes p to
//     distance_squared (so p escapes), so all adds materialize.
//
// What this fixture does today:
//   - Parses + validates cleanly (`sutrac` reports 0 diagnostics).
//   - Runs end-to-end but the return value is a vector, not a clean
//     int. Scalars stored in an axon round-trip back as vector
//     approximations (fuzzy by default per Sutra's substrate
//     semantics). To recover a crisp int, the lowering would need
//     an explicit `.real()` projection at the use site — that's a
//     separate piece of work, parallel to the String class.

function int distance_squared(Axon p) {
    return p.item("x") * p.item("x") + p.item("y") * p.item("y");
}

function int main() {
    Axon p;
    p.add("x", 3);
    p.add("y", 4);
    return distance_squared(p);
}
